Introduction

In this assignment, we aims to introduce a technique called order stars, which provides us with a better understanding of stability theories. Padé approximations and multiple real pole approximation is mainly discussed in this article.

Stability Functions

Introduction of stability function

The idea of stability functions is initially raised by Dahlquist in 1963. One simple example is presented in the application of implicit Euler method to Dahlquist's equation y′=λy. In detail, the local linearisation on y=y0 with stepsize h gives the linear equation y1=y0+hλy1. We notice that y1=R(hλ)y0 converges for each y0 whence |R(z)|=1|1−z|<1.

Stability function of Runge-Kutta method

The r-stage RK-method is given in form of

Kj=f(tn+cjh,yn+h∑i=1raijKi)yn+1=yn+h∑j=1rbjKj.

For y′=λy, it yields that K=zAK+λyn, where

K=(K1,K2,…,Kr)∈Rr.

Hence

(I−zA0−zbT1)⋅(K/λyn+1)=yn(11).

By taking the inverse, we obtain

(K/λyn+1)=((I−zA)−10zbT(I−zA)−11)⋅(11)⋅yn.

We deduce that yn+1=(zbT(I−zA)−11+1)yn. Therefore

R(z)=(zbT(I−zA)−11+1)=det(z1bT+I−zA)det(I−zA).

Consider the exact solution y1=ez⋅y0, we say the RK method is of order p whence

ez−R(z)=Czp+1+O(|z|p+2),|z|≪1,C≠0.

Absolute stability

The stability domain is defined as D:={z:|R(z)|<1}. For arbitrary y0 and each z∈D in a Dahlquist equation, it yields that yn=(R(z))ny0→0 as n→∞.

For ODEs, a method is absolute stable (A-stable in short) whence S⊃C−={z:Re(z)<0}. A RK method with R(z)=P(z)Q(z) is A-stable whenever the following conditions holds

  • |R(iy)|≤1 for each y∈R.
  • R(z) is analytic on C−.

Padé Approximations

In comparision of the numerical estimate y1=R(z)y0 and the explicit solution y1=ezy0, we say the RK method is of order s whence ezQ(z)=P(z)+C1zs+1+C2zs+2+⋯. Here P(z) and Q(z) are polynomials with degree ≤s, P(0)=Q(0)=1. It is clear that Ci's are uniquely determined by Q(z).

For Q(z)=∑i=0sqizi​ (q0=1​), taking Taylor expansion yields that

P(z)=∑k=0s(∑i=0kqi(k−i)!)zk=q0+(q10!+q01!)z+⋯+(q0s!+q1(s−1)!+⋯+qs1!)zs.

We also deduce the error constants Cj=∑i=0sqi(s+j−i)!. In order to symmetrise P(z) and Q(z), we introduce the M-ploynomial

M(x):=∑k=0sxkk!qs−k.

Hence Q(z)=∑i=0sM(s)(0)zs−i, P(z)=∑i=0sM(s)(1)zs−i. The error constants are given by integrals, i.e., C1=∫01M(x)dx, C2=∫01(1−x)M(x)dx.

Nørsett and Wanner (1979) shows M(x)=u(x) for collocation method based on points {ci}i=1s, provided that

u(x)=(s!)−1∏i=1s(x−ci).

The main idea of Padé's work is to estimates ez with rational function P(z)Q(z) to the greatest extent. We shall summerise his construction as follows:

One notices that M(x)=xk(x−1)j(k+j)! satisfies M(i)(0)=0 for each i=0,1,…,k−1, M(i)(1)=0 for each i=0,1,…,j−1.

Hence

Pkj=∑i=0k(ki)(j+ki)zi,Qkj=∑i=0j(ji)(j+ki)(−z)i=Pjk(−z).

Let Rkj(z)=Pkj(z)Qkj(z). Then

ez−Rkj(z)=(−1)jj!k!(j+k)!(j+k+1)!zj+k+1+O(zj+k+2).

The uniqueness is due to M(k)(0)=M(j)(1)=0.

Here M(x) is called C-polynomial, which we shall discuss in the following sections.

Order Stars

Ideas of order stars

The idea of ordered stars is led to better understand whether Rjk​ fails to satisfy A-stability. It is known that R11​, the midpoint method, is A-stable. Whereas,

R15(z)=1+16z1−56z+13z2−112z3+172z4−1720z5

violates A-stability, in fact, |R15(i)|>1​. In general, R(z) is A-stable whence

  • |R(it)|≤1 for each t∈R.
  • All poles of R(z) lie in C+.

The command approx=PadeApproximant[E^z,{z,0,{1,2}}] in mathematica can be utilised to generate E12.

The definition of order star is given by

A={z∈C:|q(z)|>1}.

Here q(z):=R(z)ez is called the order star of R. It is clear that the order star is symmertric w.r.t. real axis. As a immediate corollary, R(z) is A-stable whence A∩iR=∅ and all poles of q(z) lies in C+.

Star Structure

The star structure of R15 can be visualised by the following codes (in mathematica)

Needs["FunctionApproximations`"];
approx = PadeApproximant[E^z, {z, 0, {2, 4}}];
OrderStarPlot[approx, E^z]
xxxxxxxxxx
ComplexPlot[approx, {z, -7 - 7 I, 7 + 7 I}]

The ComplexPlot command fails to plots the star structure of A, due to the lack of accuracy near the origin.

The star structure has the following behaviours.

The even partition near the origin

One notices that the order stars gives the even partition in the vicinity of the origin. This is due to the error formula

q(z)−1=Czs+1+O(zs+2)

induces an s+1-covering map near the origin.

The asymptomatic behaviour as r→∞

One notices that

  • for fixed θ∈(−π/2,π/2), there exists r(θ)>0 such that reiθ∉A as r>r(θ).
  • for fixed θ∈(π/2,3π/2), there exists r(θ)>0 such that reiθ∈A as r>r(θ).

This is due to |ez| is much stronger than each given polynomial as Re(z)>0; much weaker if Re(z)<0.

Moreover, the border ∂A possesses only two branches which go to infinity. If R(z)=Kzl+O(zl−1) for z→∞, then the branches asymptotically approach x=log⁡|K|+llog⁡|y|.

Proof. Let

φ1(θ)=|ez|2=e2rcos⁡θ,φ2(θ)=|R(z)|2=R(reiθ)R(re−iθ).

Then (log⁡φ1)θ=−2rsin⁡θ, (log⁡φ2)θ=2rRe(ieiθR′(reiθ)R(reiθ)).

Since R′(z)R(z)→0 as z→∞, there exists ε>0 such that

(log⁡φ1)θ<(log⁡φ2)θ,θ∈[ε,π−ε].

There exists exact one θ such that φ1(θ)=φ2(θ), thus θ can regarded as a function of r (as well as fome fixed ε for each r). As a consequence, the intersection of |R(z)| and |ez| lying in

∪r∈R(r×{[ε,π−ε]})⊂H

is the curve θ(r). Since |K|⋅rl=ex+O(rl−1), we deduce that

log⁡|K|+llog⁡|y|(1+E1(z))=x⋅(1+E2(z)).

Here

  • E1(z)→0 as r→∞, since yx→0 as r→∞.
  • limr→∞p(r)=E2(r)→0 for each polynomial p(r).

Thus we deduce the desired approximation

x=log⁡|K|+llog⁡|y|.
The poles in each white fingers

We claim that each bounded white sector at the origin contains at least a pole. Moreover, the number of exponentional fitting points #{z∈∂A:R(z)=ez} equals the the number of poles (counting multiplicities).

Proof. For a sector Ω with ∂Ω⊂∂A. Let γ:[s0,s1]→C be a parametrisation of ∂Ω such that |γ′|≡1. Then s→=(x(s)′,y(s)′) is a tengent vector along ∂Ω, n→=(y(s)′,−x(s)′) is a (exterior) normal vector. Write q(z)=q(x+iy) as r(x,y)⋅eiφ(x,y).

First, ∇n→(log⁡r)≤0 since log⁡r increases in Ω. The Cauchy-Riemann equation gives

∇t→(φ)=∇xφ+∇yφ=−∇yr+∇xr=∇n→(φ)≤0.

Consider t→⋅q′(γ(s))=i⋅q(γ(s))⋅∇t→(φ). It reveals that ∇t→(φ)≠0 except finite many points (that is, exponentional fitting points). Thus the vector q(z) along the contour curve γ(t) revolution at least 2π every when finishing a loop in ∂Ω. Since the total change of arguments are at least m⋅2π, the the m sectors contains at least m poles (counting multiplicities).

We claim that the number of exponentional fitting points #{z∈∂A:R(z)=ez} equals the the number of poles (counting multiplicities). Indeed, the number of exponentional fitting points are as many as the loops in ∂Ω, due to ∇t→(φ) is monotonous.

Order stars for rational approximations

Let R(z) be a rational approximation of order s, with m0 zeros and m∞ poles. Then we have the following theorems:

Theorem 1. When R(z) is A-stable, then the number of different zeros in C− is no less than s−22.

Proof. It reveals that A has at least k1 white sectors in C−. Otherwise, some of the arguments of the poles exceed [−π/2,π/2].

Theorem 2. Suppose s≥2m∞−1, |R(∞)|≤1, then R(z) is A-stable.

Proof. |R(∞)|≤1 implies m0≤m∞. One notices that at least ⌊(s+1)/2⌋ sectors start in C+ and cannot cross the imaginary axis, thus must be bounded. As a result, the number of poles in C+ is no less than ⌊(s+1)/2⌋.

We claim that all poles are simple, since the second equality holds in the following inequality,

⌊(s+1)/2⌋≤#{poles in C+}≤m∞≤s+12.

Therefore, all poles are in C+. It (with |R(∞)|≤1) yields that R(z) is A-stable.

Theorem 3. Suppose s≥2m∞−3, |R(∞)|≤1, and the coefficients of Q(z) have alternating signs, then R(z) is A-stable.

Proof. Similarly, we deduce that

⌊(s+1)/2⌋≤#{poles in C+}≤m∞≤s+32

Then we have either 0 or 1 pole in C−. Assume that the latter holds, the symmetry implies that the pole must be on R−. One notice that Q(x)≠0 for x∈R−, which contradicts our assumption.

Theorem 4. Let m0′ and m∞′ denotes the number of distinct zeros and poles. Then m0′+m∞′≥s.

Proof. One shall regard the order star as a CW-complex in C― (the ∞-compactification of R​). Via

2=χ(C―)=∑ℓ=02(−1)ℓ⋅sℓ≤1−(p+1)+(m0′+m∞′+2),

one obtains m0′+m∞′≥s.

Here s1≥p+1, s2≤m0′+m∞′+2.

Theorem 5. (Theorem and Conjecture of Ehle) Rkj is A-stable whence k≤j≤k+2. All poles and zeros are simple.

Proof. ⇐: |R(∞)|≤i equals j≥k. When all poles are in C+, j≤k+2.

⇒: If j≤k+2, then s≥2j−2, thus j≤k+2. Moreover, |R(∞)|≤i equals j≥k.

The inequality

m0′+m∞′≥s=j+k

reveals all poles and zeros are simple.

A-Stability of restricted Padé approximations.

Intorduction to Laguerre polynomials

The Lagguerre polynomial is utilised for Gaussian quadrature to numerically compute integrals of the form

∫0∞f(x)e−xdx.

Since (ddx−1)ex=0​, we can conclude that

Ln(x)=1n!(ddx−1)nxn.

The inner product is defined as

⟨f,g⟩:=∫0∞f(x)g(x)e−xdx.

For alrge values, we have Hilb's asymptotic formula

Lk(x)=ex/2πxk⋅(cos⁡[2xk−π/4]+xk⋅O(1)).

Multiple real pole approximation

The motivation

The stability function of real pole approximation has real poles only, i.e., all poles of Q(z) are on R. By symmertry, each white finger in A is enclosed by a black finger in C−A. As a result, the remaining (finite) s−1 sectors contains at least s−1 zeros.

We conclude that the order of real pole approximation is at most deg⁡P+1.

In order to estimate R(A) more efficiently, we hope Q(A)=(I−γA)p. A multiple real pole approximation of e−x is of the form

Rpm(z)=∑i=0maixi(1+zx)p.

In fact, there exists m different choice of z such that the resulting order is m+1 (optimal order).

C polynomial

The M(x) defined in the previous section is given by

M(x)=xk(x−1)j(k+j)!.

As a consequence, we deduce that

R(x)=P(x)Q(x)=∑i=0sM(s)(1)xs−i∑i=0sM(s)(0)xs−i.

As for multiple real pole approximation, we have

Spm(x)=∑j=0mMp(p−j)(z;0)xj∑j=0mMp(p−j)(z;1)xj.

Here Spm(x) denotes some Rpm(x) with order at least m​. Since

Mp(p−j)(z;1)=(−1)p+jzjLp(p−j)(0)=zj(pj),

we obtian that ∑j=0mMp(p−j)(z;1)xj=(1+zx)p.

As a consequence,

Spm(x)=∑j=0m(−1)p+jLp(p−j)(z−1)(zx)j(1+zx)p=γ=−z∑j=0m(−1)jLp(p−j)(γ−1)(γx)j(1−γx)p.

The error constant is C=(−1)j+1γkk+1Lk+1′(γ−1). As a result, the optimal order attains whenever Lk+1′(γ−1)′=0. We write γ1−1<γ2−1<⋯<γk−1.

For such γν's, the order star for restricted Padé approximation contains one bounded finger with multiplicity k−ν+1.

As a corollary, the restrict Padé approximation with optimal order is A-stable if

⌊k/2⌋≤ν≤⌊(k+1)/2⌋.

Proof. There are k−ν+1 fingers begins in C+, ν−1 fingers begin in C−. We claim at most k+2 fingers starts in C+ or in C−. If not, then some fingers must cross the imaginary axis, which contradicts the A-stability.

The optimal order of A-stable restrict Padé approximation

The restrict Padé approximation is A-stable whenever

Lk(γν−1)=limz→∞|R(z)|≤1.

By Hilb's asymptotic formula, we obtains the ν-th extremum point of Lk+1​ is approximately

xν=π2(ν+1/4)24(k+1).

By |L(xν)|>1, we obtains the following proposition

k≥{1ν=1,5ν=2,9ν=3,6ν−10ν≥4.
